Alle Aufgaben sollen in einem Jupyter Notebook mit Python bearbeitet werden.

Aufgabe 1¶

In der Datei iris.csv finden Sie den Iris-Datensatz.

  1. Lesen Sie die Datei mit pandas ein.
  2. Erstellen Sie Plots fr alle Features (d.h. fr die ersten vier Spalten). Hierfr verwenden Sie Histogramme und Scatterplots. In den Plots sollen die unterschiedlichen "species" erkenntlich sein.
  3. Berechnen Sie fr alle species und alle Features den Mittelwert, die Standardabweichung, den Median und den sogenannten Inter quartile range (IQR), der definiert ist als die Differenz des 75%-Quantil und des 25%-Quantil (Hinweis: Verwenden Sie np.quantile oder die quantile-Methode von pandas Series).

In [10]:
# a histogram for each feature (outer loop);
# make a separate histogram for each species (inner loop).
# At the end of the inner loop, plt.show() finishes the current plot (s.t. later hists are placed into a new plot).
# We use alpha=0.5 to make it possible to distinguish the species.

for colname in df.columns[:4]:
    for species in df["species"].unique():
        idx = df["species"]==species
        plt.hist ( df[idx].loc[:,colname], alpha=0.5, label=species )
    plt.title(colname)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# note that the bin widths are not comparable in the histograms.
# (Especially in the last plot).
# it is a good practice to use common bins whenever different histograms
# are plotted in the same window.

for colname in df.columns[:4]:
    value_min = df.loc[:,colname].min()
    value_max = df.loc[:,colname].max()
    bins = np.linspace(value_min,value_max,20)
    
    for species in df["species"].unique():
        idx = df["species"]==species
        plt.hist ( df[idx].loc[:,colname], alpha=0.5, label=species, bins=bins )
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

  • Scatterplots
In [36]:
# in the outer loop(s), we loop over all pairs of columns for which we want to create a scatterplot.
# Again, in the inner loop, we plot the different species.
#
# The usage of enumerate in the outer loops is a common construction to get all ordered pairs, i.e. to avoid
# (2,1) if (1,2) has already been plotted.

# for i,c1 in enumerate(df.columns[:4]):
#     for j,c2 in enumerate(df.columns[:4]):
#         if i >= j: continue

for i,c1 in enumerate(df.columns[:4]):
    for j,c2 in enumerate(df.columns[:4]):
        if i >= j: continue
        
        for species in df["species"].unique():
            idx = df["species"]==species
            plt.scatter ( df[idx].loc[:,c1], df[idx].loc[:,c2], alpha=0.5, label=species )
        
        plt.xlabel(c1)
        plt.ylabel(c2)
        plt.title("{0} vs {1}".format(c1,c2))
        plt.legend()
        plt.show()

# a lambda function is anonymous, i.e. does not have a __name__ entry. This is ugly in the aggregation result.
# we can fix this by renaming the result manually
df.groupby("species").agg( [np.mean, np.std, np.median, lambda x: x.quantile(0.75)-x.quantile(0.25)] ) \
    .rename({"<lambda_0>":"iqr"},axis=1)

# In excercise, the goal is to look beyond the univariate frequencies/importances "per word".
# We look at the correlation (more precisely: the cosine similarity) of two word's occurency-in-the-abstracts vectors.
# An equally valid approach would be to count bi-grams and evaluate their importance just as we did in 2.1 and 2.2
# for single words.
# The difference:
# - bi-grams ask for word pairs that appear next to each other (in particular, in the same abstract)
# - while correlations/cosine similarities ask only for "occurs in the same abstract" (not necessarily next to each other)

In [201]:
%%time

# iterate through all pairs of columns and collect the number of co-occurencies
cooc = {}

for i,c1 in enumerate(docterm_imp.columns):
    for j,c2 in enumerate(docterm_imp.columns):
        if i==j: continue
        #if i>=j: continue
        
        # count how often the words c1, c2 occur together
        co_occurencies = (docterm_imp.loc[:,c1]*docterm_imp.loc[:,c2]).sum()
        
        # normalize with the individual frequencies.
        # use the square root to get the result 1 if we compare a vector to itself.
        # (Note: this metric is called cosine similarity.)
        co_occurencies /= np.sqrt ( docterm_imp.loc[:,c1].sum()*docterm_imp.loc[:,c2].sum() )
        
        # store in the result
        cooc[(c1,c2)] = co_occurencies
